In this section we estimate the number of microlensing events with possible red giant-lens and negative-parity image eclipsing. We use data from OGLE III catalog where for simple microlensing events the best values of light curve from the Markov Chain Monte-Carlo fitting is estimated \citep{ogleIII}. The blending parameter estimated for the light curves indicate the contribution of the flux from of background stars. Figure (\ref{blend}) shows the distribution of blending parameter for this set of database. Small blending parameter (i.e. $b\ll 1$) means large blending contribution to the flux of source star from the background stars. This blending can be due to either stars around the source star at the background or it might be due to a red-giant lens star. In order to limit the blending parameter with a possible red-giant lens star, we assume a red giant with $F>10 F_\odot$, source star is a solar-type star and lens is located at the middle of observer-source distance. This means that the blending parameter is $b<0.02$. 



Figure (\ref{cm}) shows the distribution of microlensing events from OGLE III catalog in the color-magnitude (CM) diagram. Here we use $2614$ events from OGLE III microlensing candidates where they have photometry data both in $I$ and $V$ bands. We identified $24$ events in the red giant region where $V-I>2$ and $I<17.5$ and the blending parameter of $b<0.02$. For this subsample of events, either background stars within PSF of source star or lens star might be a red-giant. Table (\ref{table1}) is the list of microlensing candidates from OGLE III catalog that satisfy the mentioned conditions. From the light curve of these events, taking into account the cadence and the photometry uncertainty around the peak of microlensing light curve, eleven candidate have significant signal of gravitational microlensing, however for the rest of events the microlensing signal is weak. Figure (\ref{sample}) shows event OGLE-2006-BLG-270 as a sample of high cadence event from Table (\ref{table1}).  

In order to make a follow-up observation to detect the eclipse of negative parity image by the lens star, first we have to decrease the blending parameter as much possible with high quality imaging methods. Recent observational methods as the lucky imaging camera decreases the turbulent effects of the atmosphere with high frequency imaging and can produce images even in the diffraction limit of telescope \citep{lucky}. Recent observations with this method has been used for identifying possible time variation of asteroids \citep{mancini}. The advantage of using lucky imaging technique to decrease the blending effect is that, if the blending with this procedure is not decreased, then regarding the position of star in the color-magnitude diagram, it is more likely that the blending effect is due to a bright red-giant lens star.  Then from measuring the blending parameter, we can estimate the size of red giant lens star and consequently the time of eclipsing the negative parity images of lensing. Finally to identify small variation of flux due to image eclipsing, we can use the telescope defocusing method to increase the signal to noise ratio by gathering as much as photons from the source star. 





























\section{Conclusion}
\label{conc}
In this work, we proposed the observation of eclipse of negative parity image from single-lens microlensing events. The gravitational lensing produces two images at the either sides of lens star and the small image with negative parity is fainter and closer to the lens position. For a large enough impact parameter the position of the negative parity image can be so closer to the lens star that is eclipsed by the lens star. In this case we will miss the second image and the overall flux receiving from the source and lens star gets dimmer. We investigate the eclipsing moment with respect to the maximum magnification time of microlensing and calculate the light curve during the eclipse. 

We studied $2614$ microlensing candidates from OGLE III catalog and $24$ events are at the position of red-giant in the color-magnitude diagram and have large blending (i.e. $b\ll 1$) with the background stars. These candidates are potential events having red-giant lens stars. In order to filter out events with this specification, we propose observing these events with a lucky imaging camera. This imaging method produces very sharp images and with selecting the best frames, we can even reach to the diffraction limit of the telescope. The result would be decreasing the blending of the source star and in the case that blending doesn't change, then the lens star of these events are more likely to be a red-giant star. Finally we propose using the high photometry precision method like defocusing of telescope for detecting small variations of flux in the order of $\sim 10^{-5}$ during negative parity image eclipsing. 

With the present microlensing follow-up telescopes and equipments as lucky imaging camera, the observation of this phenomenon is doable. 




